            <h5 class="center">The Stable</h5>

            <p class="light">All professional sumo wrestlers began their careers as youngsters in a communal environment known as a stable. Stables contain all of the people who are involved in the production of sumo wrestling including hairdressers, referees, and retired sumo wrestlers who conduct training sessions. These communes are run by a stable master and his wife - an oyakata and okamisan - with the goal of preserving and teaching the various disciplines and traditions of sumo wrestling.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="col s12 m4">
          <div class="icon-block">
            <h2 class="center red-text"><i class="material-icons">info</i></h2>
            <h5 class="center">The Rules</h5>

            <p class="light">A sumo wrestling match concludes when one of the wrestlers is either knocked out of the ring or hits the sand with any part of his body other than his feet. There are also illegal moves that disqualify a wrestler such as hair pulling or punching with a closed fist.</p>
          </div>
